Q01 [MID] | Concurrency
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
QUESTION:
  Explain the difference between a goroutine and an OS thread.
  Why are goroutines cheaper?

ANSWER:
  Goroutines are multiplexed onto a small number of OS threads by the Go
  runtime scheduler using an M:N scheduling model (M goroutines on N threads).

  Key differences:
  ┌──────────────────────┬────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────┐
  │ Aspect               │ OS Thread              │ Goroutine                │
  ├──────────────────────┼────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
  │ Stack size           │ ~1–8 MB (fixed)        │ ~2–8 KB (grows/shrinks)  │
  │ Context switch       │ Kernel space (costly)  │ User space (fast)        │
  │ Scheduling           │ OS scheduler           │ Go runtime scheduler     │
  │ Creation cost        │ High                   │ Very low                 │
  │ Typical count        │ Hundreds               │ Millions possible        │
  └──────────────────────┴────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────┘

  The Go runtime dynamically resizes goroutine stacks using stack copying.
  Context switching happens entirely in user space, avoiding expensive
  system calls.

  Java comparison:
    Java virtual threads (Project Loom, Java 21) are analogous — also
    lightweight, multiplexed over OS threads. Go had this model from day one.

  Code example:
    go func() {
        fmt.Println("I'm a goroutine")
    }()
    // Spawning 1 million of these is feasible in Go

