Q04 [MID] | Interfaces
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
QUESTION:
  What is implicit interface satisfaction in Go and why does it matter?

ANSWER:
  In Go, a type satisfies an interface automatically if it implements all
  the methods in the interface. There is no "implements" keyword.

  Why it matters:
    1. Loose coupling — packages can define small interfaces over types
       from other packages without creating circular imports.
    2. Testability — you can define a local interface that your real
       dependency satisfies, then mock it in tests.
    3. Composability — small interfaces (io.Reader, io.Writer) combine
       naturally via embedding.

  Code example:
    type Stringer interface {
        String() string
    }

    type User struct { Name string }

    // User implicitly satisfies Stringer — no declaration needed
    func (u User) String() string { return u.Name }

    func Print(s Stringer) { fmt.Println(s.String()) }

    // Verify at compile time (idiom):
    var _ Stringer = User{}

  Java comparison:
    Java uses explicit "implements Stringer" — Go's implicit model allows
    retrofitting any existing type to satisfy a new interface without
    modifying it.

