Q09 [MID] | Generics
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
QUESTION:
  Explain Go generics type constraints. What is comparable?

ANSWER:
  Generics (added Go 1.18) allow functions and types to be parameterized
  over types. Type constraints restrict what types are valid.

  Constraint syntax:
    func Map[T any, R any](s []T, f func(T) R) []R { ... }

    // Union constraint — only int or float64
    type Number interface {
        int | float64
    }
    func Sum[T Number](s []T) T { ... }

  comparable:
    A built-in constraint meaning the type supports == and !=.
    Required to use a type as a map key inside a generic function.

    func Contains[T comparable](s []T, v T) bool {
        for _, item := range s {
            if item == v { return true }
        }
        return false
    }

  Note: any is an alias for interface{} — the most permissive constraint.
  comparable is stricter — interfaces and slices do NOT satisfy it.

  Java comparison:
    Similar to Java generics bounded wildcards (<T extends Number>), but
    Go constraints are plain interfaces, not a separate syntax.

