Q10 [MID] | Design
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
QUESTION:
  What is the "accept interfaces, return structs" principle in Go?

ANSWER:
  Accept interfaces (in parameters):
    Functions should accept interface types so callers can pass any
    conforming implementation — enabling mocks in tests and flexible
    composition without modifying the function.

  Return structs (as return types):
    Return concrete types so callers have access to the full type without
    type-asserting. It also keeps APIs stable — adding methods to a
    returned interface is a breaking change.

  Code example:
    // GOOD — accepts interface (testable), returns struct (concrete)
    func NewCache(store Storage) *Cache {
        return &Cache{store: store}
    }

    // BAD — returns interface (forces type assertion, hides type)
    func NewCache(store Storage) Storage {
        return &Cache{store: store}
    }

  Exception: returning an error interface is idiomatic (it IS the
  convention in Go). Also, factory functions returning an interface make
  sense when hiding implementation is the explicit design goal.

  Java comparison:
    Java often returns interface types (List instead of ArrayList) for
    flexibility. Go inverts this — return the concrete type; the caller
    decides what interface to view it through.

