Q12 [SENIOR] | Memory & Runtime
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
QUESTION:
  How does the Go garbage collector work? What causes GC pressure
  and how do you reduce it?

ANSWER:
  Go GC algorithm:
    Concurrent tri-color mark-and-sweep with short stop-the-world (STW)
    pauses. Phases:
      1. Mark setup (STW — milliseconds)
      2. Concurrent mark — marks live objects while program runs
      3. Mark termination (STW)
      4. Concurrent sweep — reclaims dead objects concurrently

  GC is triggered when heap doubles from last GC (GOGC=100 default).
  Lower GOGC = more frequent GC, less memory use, more CPU.
  Higher GOGC = less frequent GC, more memory use, less CPU.

  What causes GC pressure:
    - Many short-lived heap allocations in hot paths
    - Interface boxing (value stored in interface escapes to heap)
    - Closures capturing variables (may cause heap allocation)
    - Appending to slices beyond capacity (reallocations)
    - String concatenation in loops (creates intermediate strings)

  How to reduce:
  ┌─────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ Technique                       │ Details                              │
  ├─────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ sync.Pool                       │ Reuse objects across goroutines      │
  │ Preallocate slices/maps         │ make([]T, 0, knownCap)              │
  │ Use concrete types not interface│ Avoids boxing / heap escape          │
  │ strings.Builder                 │ Avoids intermediate string allocs    │
  │ Reduce pointer density          │ Flat structs with values, not ptrs   │
  │ GOGC tuning                     │ Increase for latency-sensitive apps  │
  └─────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────┘

  Profiling:
    go tool pprof cpu.prof       // CPU profile
    go tool pprof -alloc_space   // allocation profile (heap)
    GODEBUG=gctrace=1            // print GC stats to stderr

  Java comparison:
    Go GC is simpler (no generational GC) — tradeoff is that all objects
    are in one heap. Java's G1/ZGC has generational collection.
    Go compensates by encouraging stack allocation via escape analysis.

