Q17 [SENIOR] | Channels
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
QUESTION:
  Explain the select statement. How do you implement a timeout and a
  non-blocking channel operation?

ANSWER:
  select blocks until one of its cases is ready, then executes that case.
  If multiple cases are ready simultaneously, one is chosen at random.

  Basic select:
    select {
    case msg := <-ch1:
        fmt.Println("received from ch1:", msg)
    case ch2 <- "hello":
        fmt.Println("sent to ch2")
    }

  Timeout using time.After:
    select {
    case result := <-work:
        fmt.Println("got result:", result)
    case <-time.After(5 * time.Second):
        fmt.Println("timed out")
    }

  Production preference — context.WithTimeout (avoids timer leak):
    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 5*time.Second)
    defer cancel()

    select {
    case result := <-work:
        fmt.Println("got result:", result)
    case <-ctx.Done():
        fmt.Println("timed out:", ctx.Err())
    }

  Non-blocking channel operation (default branch):
    select {
    case msg := <-ch:
        fmt.Println("got:", msg)
    default:
        fmt.Println("no message ready — continuing")
    }

  Why context over time.After:
    time.After creates a timer that leaks until it fires if the case
    is selected early. context.WithTimeout is cancelled via defer cancel(),
    cleaning up the timer properly.

  Java comparison:
    select ≈ CompletableFuture.anyOf() but synchronous and channel-based.
    Timeout ≈ Future.get(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS).

